I continued with the "delete_email" method in the Inbox class for the "Build an Email Simulation" workshop in freeCodeCamps Python certificate.
First I converted the 1-based index back to 0 via the "actual_index" attribute. Then I handled the case where a User tries to delete an email at
an invalid index with an if-statement thats checks wheter the actual_index is less then 0 or equal or greater then the actual length of the emails list.
I added the del() function to delete an email, if emails is not empty and is a valid index.
I imported the "datetime" method so that the "display_full_email" and "__str__" methods in the Email class could show the date and time of the emails received. 
For that I added an attributed called "timestamp" to the "__init__" method in which the current date time is saved. Then I used the "strf()" function so I could
print out the year, month, day, hour and minute separated either by an "-" or ":".
I also added a feedback for the user, so it's clear that the email was succesfully send using a print statement in the send_email method.
Then I added the methods check_inbox,read_email, delete_email to the User class, with a call back to the acutall methods created earlier.
To test and to close this project, I added the main() function and created to users.
